segments.text: check this in just a minute and see if we are.
Okay, if you'll begin by telling me your name and where you were born.
Well, I was born in Musquis, Coahuila, Mexico.
And my name was given to me was Guadalupe Garza.
Then my mother and my daddy come to the United States in
In August the 26th, 1926, we passed through Eagle Pass.
And since then, we've been given in the United States.
Yeah, I mean in Texas since then.
And then we grew up over here in the, what you call, the brass bottom.
And we went to school over there.
We were 12 in the family, six boys and six girls.
And my daddy was...

farmer or agriculture, we used to plant cotton, corn in the fields, and we used to help them during the, not during the school period, but during the harvest, we used to help them and pull the cotton, pick the cotton, and then my, every year, you know, at the end of the year, my daddy will equalize the whole crop and then give them money,
But I think those days were happy days to us.
And all of my brothers and sisters, we all went to school.
We got all that good education.
I mean, not high school, but some got towards ninth grade, 10th grade, in those days.
And I think that was good.
And so all my family moved to the state of Oklahoma.
And they all live over there except me.
I live here.
But then I got married in 1942.
I got married to Mr. Medina.
And then we... What is his first name?
Julio.
Julio Medina.
Julio C. Contreras Medina.
And he works at the MSC as a cook.
He's doing a little vacation in Mexico.
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, he's there.
They called this morning from...
from close to Monterrey.
My daughter and my son-in-law, they went over there.
So then my daddy, before he come to the United States, he was born in Muscas, also in the same state and the same city we were born.
What did his father do in Muscas?
That would be your grandfather.
I really don't remember, but I believe in those early days.
Before the Revolution.
Before the Revolution.
I guess all of it was like a farmer, you know.
They have their little crops and all that.
Did they have their own land?
Well, they never did mention no land, but I think they were not well off.
But they were, you know, just making a living somewhere over there in Mooskies.
And so, I remember my grandfather.
I remember him and my grandma.
I remember both.
And I remember when grandpa, in 1934, no, it's 1932, my father-in-law, my grandfather, his name was Martiniano Garza, he passed away.
And I remember to this day, I was about six years old, but I remember that they make a casket, you know, with some new boars, and they put some linen, and all this means put in a wagon.
And we took him, and he was buried over here at Snoop.
No, Tunis.
That's where he's buried.
Then in 1934, Grandma passed away, and we did the same thing.
And I still remember the roll and the wagon and everything.
You know, the funerals those days, we didn't even touch no ambulance, no nothing.
We just made our own funeral.
But I remember seeing the father, because they were Catholic.
I remember the father went and gave her the blessing.
I remember that real good, because they

took the father from here to Bryant, to the farm, and he gave all the church rights, and then she passed away that day, and then the father said, well, and nobody complained, and nobody said nothing, no ambulance, no nothing, but it was this wagon.
I remember we were little.
We all climbed on the wagon.
And they had about four or five wagons, of course.
All the people from the same, these men that called themselves Porres, they owned all those lands over there.
So we took one more over there into the graveyard.
But I still remember that this minister took part in the service of the graveyard.
And he read the rights.
But then I was seven years old.
I remember then.
I remember then when he got some dirt and say, ashes to ashes and all that.
And I know that man to date, but I never had the knowledge or the thinking to tell him that I know him, that he went and performed a run ball field.
But I don't know what happened.
Every time I wanted to tell him something, it had to happen.
But I really wanted to tell him that he was the one that went over there.
But I don't know who I am.
I kind of put it off every time I get a conversation.
I want to tell him, but I don't know.
I have to go and tell him that he was the first man that I...
that I heard say something about God or something, like that other Bible or something.
Because we, all the background, we didn't have no, we never did go to church.
Nobody teach us nothing.
Nobody say nothing.
We were just living in the farm, you know, way far from the other people.
We didn't know nobody.
Yeah, but your family was Catholic at that time.
Yeah, my family was Catholic, so the priest went over there.
But in Mexico, my father was a, well, he was a,
I think his rank was a cap in the military service.
But you see that their Revolution War was bad.
Well, let's begin kind of at the beginning.
What year was your father born?
Well, I don't remember that.
How old is he now?
He's 89.
He's 89 now.
I think he was born about 1870.
He was born in the early 1880s.
So when the Revolution came, he was probably in his late 20s or early 30s.
Yeah, he was.
Well, when my daddy entered the service, he said he was just 12 years old.
Was he in the Army before the Revolution?
No, but he had some military background.
He had some military background before it happened.
By 12, he was already a military man.
And was he then in the Dias troops, the federal troops?
Something like that, but he got to know Pancho Villa, that's for sure.
And I wish he was here, I'd ask him, and he'd tell me, yes, I know Pancho Villa, you know, in person.
He always tried to describe us, the men, but we just
He didn't believe and didn't think this was too serious.
And we told him that what kind of a man was he.
And he said, oh, he was a, what you call it, go-getter.
He was a mean man.
He said, yeah, that's one thing they have to say, that he was a mean man.
Because if things don't go his way, he'd kill anybody.
No matter if it was a kid or a little girl or a boy or a woman or anybody.
A man, it didn't make him no bigger.
And your father was a soldier with Villa?
No, my father was a soldier, but this is Pablo Gonzlez.
Pablo Gonzlez.
Pablo Gonzlez.
Yeah, Pablo Gonzlez.
And now I've been reading a little history, and I see those names, but I don't know who the person was.
But he was Pablo Gonzlez and another by the name of Huerta.
Victoriano Huerta, and your father was with Huerta and Gonzales.
Every time he said Pablo Gonzales, he was his captain or something, but my daddy had a good military background in military service.
He was actually fighting against Villa.
Well, yes, he was fighting against Villa because he died thinking that he was doing right.
But he said, no, he was not doing right, because he killed more people, innocent people, than people that really need to be killed.
Because my daddy said that, well, we always ask, well, why are y'all the same nation, the same people?
Why did y'all have these fights against each other?
He said, well, because we were fighting against the government, against the government, because the government didn't treat the nation right, because
They didn't look for the poor or they didn't help the poor.
And then I asked the question, how much money did you earn?
About a month or a week.
Nobody had no payroll.
They had to go up to the cities and rob the banks and the stores and give things what they needed.
Of course, they had the power because they had guns where they wouldn't grab anything to eat.
They'd go through fields and ranches and all that thing.
They'd kill cows and make

still barbecue there and then eat it and then take off to another time but he said the main thing we did and we know that we did he said fight it against the government because he they they was not treating the people right he said if the family was living over here and having two or three girls if a man abused one of the girls there was no law instead of helping well they they come and take your son you just because you told that i did wrong your son will go to the

what you call it what you call to the government federal what you call the federal government they they shaved his head uh hair off and put her what you call a cap and that was the as my father said that was the the hardest task the nation took because if you got a son and he didn't commit no crimes
Why did he have to go serve to the government?
Because somebody else did a crime.
You see, and that way the nation, the poor people was, you know, intimidated.
That way they can, if there is something wrong to your family, you can't say to the public.
If somebody did something to your family, just keep it to yourself, or else they're going to get one of your boys.
And my daddy said, well, that was that.
This was the thing that the nation, the people, the federal government did wrong.
They did wrong.
But the revolution, Villa fought.
He was fighting.
He said he was fighting against that.
Yeah, he thought, you know, he died thinking.
And, you know, I saw that way late, way, my daddy had a book.
And I don't know, he still got that book.
And I can see the man.
And I can recall the bed where he was laying.
But I don't know if he got the book yet.
But I see the wounds, you know.
It was in black and white.
I can see the wounds.
And it was a big, heavy-set man.
Heavy-set like Joe Stalin.
With big mustache.
Yeah, that was the year when he was killed.
Yeah, he was wounded.
And they had him in some kind of bed.
But I remember that book.
I don't know if he got it.
I'm going to.
I'm planning to make a trip this summer, and I'm going to get involved into all those details.
See if I can get the book and get some pictures out of it.
How many years did your father fight all together?
Oh, he fought about, I think about, he said the war started the 12th, the 8th or 9th, 8th or 9th, 10th, 11th, 12th, 13th, 14th.
I think he said about six or seven years.
before everything come to the conclusion, you know, because he said that the federal government had everything under control.
They had arms, they had rifles, they had a lot of everything.
But he said that he think that Spain had a lot to do with that.
Spain, because once Mexico was under Spain's rule, you know, the rule, and then he said all the
the most of the money and most of the gold, the Spanish people, the Spaniards from Spain took it.

And they believed that the more people that got involved in this was the priests, because all the pilgrims, all the people from the church took the gold and took everything to the church, and then the priests, when they fled out of the country, they took all that money.
So my father said that
that he believes those people did wrong, too, to the nation.
And they said that's why Mexico learned a lesson, but it was kind of hard because they have to kill each other thinking.
Like my father-in-law was telling me the other day, he said, you know, in one time, a son was fighting against his father until they would meet each other with a rifle.
He said, well, you're my father.
And they didn't shoot each other, but he said there was
almost one against each other.
And he said the main thing they was fighting for equal rights, equal rights, because he said that they want everything equal, not because somebody committed a crime, somebody else have to pay.
If I got hurt, well I have supposed to, I mean, if I got hurt, the people that hurt me,
have to pay for what he did.
Not my son, that he didn't do anything.
But you see, they had this thing so good with the government that my boy have to pay for the crime that other men commit.
He said it was a married man.
Well, he had a family.
He had something to get along by.
But not my son.
Well, you ain't got no.
Just because you told authorities this, your son will pay for that.
And this, when all the poor people got against us, they said, no, the innocents always have to pay.
We can't do that.
What did your mother do the whole time your father was fighting?
Well, you see, all the ladies stayed at home.
In Muscas?
Uh-huh, Muscas.
Was there ever any fighting in Muscas?
No, my mother used to tell us that the...
Well, I went to Monterey, yeah, to Monterey, and that's the, the mosque is not too far from Monterey.
Well, she used to talk about some mountains.
She said he hear the, you know, when they shoot the canyon, she used to hear the, you know, the booms.
And now that I saw that, I said, well, the fighting was near that, but I never did get close to that mountain where they were fighting, but it's still there.
And my mother used to say, I never did went to no war.
I never see, well, she never did see nobody fighting with the guns.
Now that's what she told me.
But she said that one day that,
that you can see the dust from the horses that were coming toward the town.
And so they yelled that, you know, they had somebody to be looking, like a guard, you know, looking and yelled that they were coming.
So they flew, flew, flee to the mountain.

And my mother said, and I took my shoes and she said she lost her shoes on the way to the mountain because she said that they had a sheet and they, all the good things they put in the sheet and they, uh,

wrap it up and took it they found a hole and put it there so that i think they went all the way over there and they got it because they they didn't stop they keep uh you know walking through the other side of the mountain get as far as they could get so my mother said you know she said they must have had her fighting before there because he said there was a man standing over there
with a big fire, you know, a big fire.
And my mother said she could see some fingers on that pile of wood they had over there.
She said she was a little girl.
She said she had her shoes like these, you know, and his arm and shoulder.
And she was walking to a little trail over there.
You know, a smoke and a big old, she thought it was wood, but it was not wood, it was the people.
It was people.
They were burning the people, yeah.
Who was burning them?
This man, this, you know, people from the, what I said, from the farm, you know, from the little village that live over there.
Because you say, you know, all that, all that odors will bring a...
Oh, they were people who were already killed.
Yeah, they were burning the bodies.
They were burning the bodies.
And then I asked my mother, why did they dig a grave?
My mother said, it would take a lifetime to dig a grave because there were rocky mountains over there.
There was nothing but rocks.
And they didn't have enough men to dig a big hole.
You know, just like a pole.
She described a pole, you know, like a
like when you put some cut on the floor, you know, about a bale of cut.
He said, that's how much the power was.
Now, my mother said, and they put a lot of branches and a lot of wood, and she think they put gasoline or kerosene, a lot of kerosene in it, so they can burn the whole thing.
But she said, when I passed through there, she said, I can see some fingers, you know, the fingers of the men, and the hands.
And this man had a fork made out of wood,
He said he was wrecking all that meat to that pile, so everything get burned.
And she said, I remember, I was a little girl then when that war, but I don't remember what year, because she never told us what year, but she used to tell us about that ugly war.
She said, and you know what?
She said, when I saw that, I asked my aunt, because she was a premature baby.
She never had no...
no sisters and no brothers from her side, because she was born, what you call a premature baby, and her grandma raised her here on her chest.
That's a little bit of her, and so his daddy got married with another woman, and she said, and then they give it to this, her godmother and godfather, she said, they raised me.
But every time those federal people come, we have to run, make a run to the mountains, because if they ever catch us, they kill us.
Did they run when the revolutionaries came, too?
No, no.
Just when the federals came?
Yeah, when the federal government came.
And my mother said that this is the same revolution, I think, but this is what they were looking for, this man by the name of Manuel.
Manuel Gardua.
They claimed that he was a big, you know, bandit or robber or something like that.
Well, my mother said that she was
my older sister, they was, you know, making some tortillas like they used to do in their little thing, what you call it?
Metate.
Metate.
And she was, and she said by the time this Gardua was there, his uncle and his cousin was there in that house where my mother lived.
In Musques.
Yes, close to the mountain in Musques.
And he said they saw the people coming, but they knew that there was not a
They were not the federal government.
They were what they called the civilians, but they were still civilian warriors.
They approached the little house.
My mother told Manuel, you better go, because they're coming after you.
And he said, no.
No, he didn't make a way, because he said, I'm not guilty of it.
They just claimed those things, but I'm not.
I'm not guilty of it.
He said, but the old man, his uncle,
It was no wiser than him because he said, all the soldiers surround the house and they were just cleaning their rifles and everything.
He said, listen, we're going to stay here a little while.
Y'all better get busy and make a lot of tortillas.
And we got some meat over here y'all can cook.
And he said, my sister and another lady and my mother started cooking for those men.
And they went and bring some wood, some more wood, because they had no stoves.
Now, mother, they had no stoves until she moved over here to Texas.
They didn't know what a stove looked like.
They cook outside an open door and some bricks or some rocks.
A hearth on the ground?
Uh-huh, on some rocks.
And so mother said, they told the men to get away from there.
He said, no, I'll stay here.
And then their uncle, who was a soldier, was standing here in the door like that with his rifle.
And that man said, excuse me, I'm going to bring the wood for the lady.
And so he jumped the soldier and took a little trail to the wood.
He never did come back.
But his mother said, there was another little tree.
She said, and us thought that this man was cruel with this other man because those days they didn't have no mercy.
They didn't give you a chance or they didn't give you a trial.
They just what you call lynch the man or just everybody just jump on you and if you were guilty or not, you have to pay for whether somebody else say.
So mother said that this man got a rope and put it over the branch of the tree and got this man neck and pulled it.
My mother said that man took his tongue about that much.
about a foot out of his mouth.
He said, you don't realize how big your tongue is until you spill it out.
You know, mother used to tell us a lot of stories, and we'd get scared.
I said, mother, why didn't you all call the law?
He said, what law?
There was no law, kids.
There was no law.
We didn't have no law and no order.
There's a reason we come to the United States to look for a better chance to live, because
You couldn't tell nobody over there the law.
Well, the law was more dirty than the other.
There was no law.
And so he said that man.
And then one of the soldiers, one of the assistant soldiers told the captain, don't do that.
Give him a chance.
Maybe he'll talk down the way they claimed they took him for a trial.
But he didn't get over there, because they kill him for the reward.
They sure believe in the reward.
Mother said that on those days anybody do something, they didn't think about the life of the man, they didn't think about their personality, nothing.
What they think is about the reward they was going to receive, no matter how they get it, but they get it.
When did your mother and father get married?
Well, they never told us nothing about that.
We were too young, I guess, or something.
We just...
They never did ask, no.
We were kind of...
We never did ask, but my mother, when she passed away, she was 63 or 65 years.
63 or so, and she died in what year?
So she was quite a bit younger than your father, probably.
Yes, she was younger than my dad.
She was younger, but you see, those couples in those days, they didn't have any...

any protection like they got on these days and the family was just a what you call it they just come handy one baby after another that's why mother had so many babies she had seven girls and six girls and six boys and out of those six boys and six girls that's one boy is dead and one we still live in ten boys and i mean five boys and five
Well, that's really remarkable for those days that all the children, or nearly all of them, lived.
And they were healthy children.
I never did remember that one went to the hospital or had tonsils or stomach aches.
We were just raised on the farm, you know, like a... Who was the oldest child in your family?
Well, my oldest sister, but she passed away.
That's the one I remember her.
Her name was Alec.
She passed in 1935.
Do you know when she was born?
No, I don't remember.
I remember one of the girls was born in 1922, and another 1923, 24, and 25.
That's me.
You were born in 25.
And my other little brother was born in 26.
Yeah, the one that's a minister, he was born in 26.
Yeah, every year, you see, I was born in December the 4th, 1926, while my brother was born in December the 2nd, 1925.
26, I was 25, and he was born in 26, just two days.
And every time we get a birthday, we are in the same week.
You see, I'm the fourth, he's the second, and I'm in the fourth.
Almost, you know, the same.
Almost the same day.
The same day.
Well, now, how did your father happen to leave Mexico?
Well, he, he, he, uh,
He just worked his way over here.
He said because he had to pay $18 for each passport.
And there was my mother, and my daddy, and my sister, they called him Alec, and Raymond, and Luis, and Eileen, and Martin, and Manuel.
There was eight kids that come from Mexico.
Now, the other ones were born over here.
they were gone.
And then my older sister, that's the one that was, that passed away, and then there was Manuel.
And out of those, out of the bring from Mexico, we still ate.
Well, you said something before about some people that wanted him to be abandoned with them before he came.
That was my father-in-law.
Your father-in-law?
Oh, I thought that was your father.
No, my father, well, my father,
My father did say something about that, too, because he said that people, after the revolution, after they got through fighting and everything come to normal, they didn't want to work.
Steel didn't want to work.
They wanted to steal and rob the other poor people.
And they were close to the soldiers, because they know how to shoot.
And my daddy, sometimes, he said, well, that's one of the reasons I come to the United States, because I was tired of the life they were living, just
sleeping on the rocks and shooting at each other just like an animal.
Let's put it that way.
We didn't even know when we were going to eat.
Sometimes we don't eat all day.
We don't drink no water.
We have nothing.
We just have to stay there.
Then my father said, I thought about it.
If I got out of the service, I'll come to the United States
And he was living in Piedras Negras, and then he moved to Eagle Pass.
When did he leave Mosques and come to Piedras Negras?
I think in 1925 that I was born.
Right, the year you were born, he moved to the border.
To the border, close to the border, because he said he was a... My daddy thinks a lot of, what you call it, shepherds.
He believes a lot on those things because he was a milkman.
Before he entered the service and after he got out of the service, he was a milkman.
He had some little goats and he delivered some milk.
And he still thinks that when he goes back, he will do that same thing.
He was a kind of shepherd.
He always lived in the woods or whatever you call it.
He believes a lot in those things.
And then he said he sell wood.
And then he started thinking he ought to give his family a chance.
He didn't want them to live like he did.
And you know those Rocky Mountains and they were no school or nothing.
But still my daddy had a good school.
My grandma believes a lot in school and they sent him to school.
They sent him to school in Moskos before the revolution.
They had a good school.
And I had an uncle, I remember him as Gregori.
He had a good school.
He was a good, well I say good sport because he knew boxing and all that.
You know, they teach the boys all that and he was a good, and then
I remember my uncle coming to visit us or to stay with us in 1932.
And he asked my daddy, well, what are you going to do with all this bunch of kids you've got and they know how to read and write?
My daddy said, well, I have to work.
I ain't got no time to deal with the kids.
He said, well, you give them to me.
He went and got those pencils.
I think you remember they were kind of a, well, I don't know.
They would make a little piece of wood, and they had a little leg.
He bought a lot of them and started teaching us.
I knew how to read and write in Spanish when I was seven years old.
And this was your uncle who was living with you right then?
And he taught you how to read and write in Spanish?
To all the family.
We didn't go to school, you know, to public school until I was 10 years old, 1935.
I was 10 years old.
How many years did you go then?
I went about five years.
But you'd had schooling in Spanish before that.
Yeah.
Do you think that helped you learn English?
Well, in a way, yes.
In a way, I say yes, but you see, it was a little harder for me because I had a little mixed up there because I thought the same thing in Spanish was in English.
until I had to forget my Spanish and start in my English.
And it was, I tell the kids, I don't suggest for nobody to know Spanish and then start in English, because it's kind of a little hard until you have to forget your Spanish and then start in English.
It's the same thing backwards.
If you know English first, it's hard to learn Spanish.
But, oh, I don't think I asked you, what town did you live in or near in the Brazos Valley?
Well, Brian.
It was right outside of Brian.
Yeah.
Well, what you call the brass bottom, they call here Mumford.
The steel store, that's where I went to school.
Steel store and Mumford.
Mumford.
Mumford.
Both schools I attended.
How did you happen to come, or how did your father happen to come here to Brian instead of staying on the border?
Let me see.
They said that we had an uncle before that.
before my dad, that he was already living here close to Hearn in a farm.
They call it Valley Johnson or Goodland.
They call it that farm.
It's a big plantation center.
They call it Goodland.
Well, he happened to live there.
So he said, I'm going to send for my brother.
They got a lot of kids to come over here, and he can live here like a king.
And I think
The way it looks, I think my uncle sent him some money because he had to pay $18.
For each one?
Each one, you know, to make the passport.
And we all got passports, and they cost $18 each one.
And some money to pay that station wagon that bought us.
Now, the station wagon in those days was what you call it?
It was just first class, like you come in a greyhound.
And my daddy said that.
That man bought also over there.
And I guess my uncle paid him and everything.
So we settled right there in that place.
And I can remember the cotton.
It must be, I don't know what, it was on August.
And I guess it was close to, you know, the cotton was about that big or something like that.
Because I can remember, you know, we still remember the farms and
and a tree that was there and everything.
Your father was actually working on the land that was owned by somebody else.
And then we moved to there.
We moved to this other place they called Scott.
It's close to this other side of the heart.
And then we moved to Mumford with this.
This man that owns these things, the seals, the seals own this place.
And then we owned with this man that he called himself Bullet.
But before that, those men, I know them.
But further down, I don't remember who was our bosses or nothing.
But I remember this one's over here.
And then we lived with the Escamados over here in the bottom.
The same Escamado, he was our boss.
And then we moved to another place they call
This, let's see, I don't remember the name.
Anyway, Ward, his name was Ward.
He owns a huge land from this river to the other river.
But what happened, he was not married man.
He didn't have no family.
So we lived there.
And that's where we went to school, to steel store.
We were staying in that place with that man.
He had a lot of farm, a lot of farm.
Well, when did your father and the rest of your family move to Oklahoma?
They moved in 1943.
Why did they move to Oklahoma?
Well, you see, the beginning of the deal was this.
We were living in Wheelock.
Well, you see, the crops over there was not so good.
So somebody that went over there by the name of Martinez called,
My daddy said, if you want to bring a bunch of people to pull some cotton, pick some cotton, we got a good place over here.
So we took a trip and we thought it was good.
And it was good and we thought it was the Holy Land because everything over there was going, you know, good.
The cotton, they paid good money and everything.
And still they pay good money over there in the state of Oklahoma.
That's the reason my daddy's black over there.
And so the boys did too, you know, because they don't work in the cities, you know, they work on the farms.
They like to...
They still work on the farms.
On the farms.
And they thought the, you know, the job was easier and better than here in Texas.
So they still, they were there.
That's their reason because they said they think they...
crops was better over there because they got an irrigation.

Well did you all travel around much when you were kids and pick crops or did you just mostly stay in the Razzus Valley and pick?
No, we traveled a lot.
We went to the state of Arkansas and we went to Tennessee.
Memphis, Tennessee.
We went over there to Arkansas and the state of Louisiana and the state of Oklahoma and the state of Texas.
Yeah, we traveled.
What was that like?
Did you enjoy it or did you dread it?
How did you feel about it?
Well, I'll put it this way.

I didn't like it, but you see, as a family kid, I have to tango along with them, but I didn't like it because I thought it was not good to be sleeping on the truck all the time and sleeping on it just like a tramp.
But I'll give you a thought about that.
I said, well, maybe when I get married, I'll settle down and don't do this.
But find out that I got married, my husband started traveling.
I said, well, you better go yourself because I'm not going.
But it was a lot of fun, all right?
You know, when you forget about everything.
It was a lot of fun when you go with a lot of girls and boys in the truck and just yell and jump off the truck and pull all day, pull cotton.
We thought it was fun.
we got to be, you know, well, we thought it was good.

So there were things about it that were really very good and fun and good memories and things that you just wouldn't have to live through again.
No, I tell my husband, I say, if you want to go, you know, places where you better go yourself.
This trip they took to Mexico.
I say, I like to go there, I say, but not

I said, for arthritis, it's not good.
You have to move, exercise.
He said, well, I stay with the kids.
You better go and enjoy yourself.
Well, you have been to Mexico, though.
Yeah, I like it over there.
I do.

Where do you work?
I work at the cashmere hatchery.
Cashmere hatchery at the hatchery.
Oh, with the baby chickens.
Yeah, what do you do?
Well, the first step we do is to set the eggs for the, what you call it, for the hatch.
And then wait for the babies to hatch.
And then, you know, we got what you call a setting every Monday and every Thursday.
Every Monday and every Thursday.
and we have to pick them out of the trays, count them, and then take to this other place.

Some sectors, they take the little rooster and the little pullet, and then all the pullets are in different boxes, and all the roosters are in different boxes, and we have to keep up with all those things.
Can you really separate them when they're that young?
Yes, because we got one...
one kind of chickens that you can tell which is which just by the wings.
Oh, that's an improvement over when I was growing up and we just had to get the little chickens and wait until they got big enough.
Yeah, well, but this kind of flock that our bosses are raising is different from the others.
You see, if you just get the little wing and open the little wing and it's made like a little fan.
as a little puller.
And if you get another one and don't have any things like a little fin or little white feathers, that's a rooster.
Well, now that's something I didn't know about yet.
That's fascinating.
That's interesting.
It sure is.
It's interesting.
And I wish more people would learn that, because they pay you good money if you don't have to separate it.
And we got some sections, they call us, some doctors from college.
They can do that, but not all the people.
But they put it to us where we can do it.
Now it's got so easy that even us, we can get a box and just pick a little chicken and just open the little feather, I mean the little wing, and you can tell.

I was a mother of nine.
Nine?
Nine, but I raised five.
I lost four little boys.
When they were babies?
Yes, they were babies.
My first baby was a little boy, and he died before he was born.
Then I had a little girl, and she didn't die.
And then I had another little boy, and he died.

and another little girl, and I have five.
